{{Infobox ancient site |name = Canalizations of Zenobia |alternate_name = |image = |alt = |caption = |map_type = Lebanon |map_alt = {{convert|900|m|ft}} |map_size = 200 |location = {{convert|26|km|mi}} northeast of [[Baalbek]] |region = [[Bekaa Valley]] |coordinates = {{coord|34.197317|36.352392|display=inline}} |type = [[Canal]]s |part_of = |length = |width = |area = |height = |builder = |material = |built = Second/third century |abandoned = |epochs = |cultures = [[Ancient Rome|Roman]], [[Byzantine]] |dependency_of = |occupants = |event = |excavations = |archaeologists = [[Diana Kirkbride]] |condition = Ruins |ownership = |management = |public_access = |website = |notes = }}
The '''Canalizations of Zenobia''' or '''El Kanat''' are [[canal]]s that according to traditions, were built by [[Queen Zenobia]] to channel water from the [[Orontes river|Orontes]] river in the [[Anti-Lebanon]] mountains to [[Palmyra]].<ref name="AloufRain1999">{{cite book|author1=Michel M. Alouf|author2=Tedd St Rain|title=History of Baalbek|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qiyY1CKE9SIC&pg=PA43|accessdate=1 October 2012|year=1999|publisher=Book Tree|isbn=978-1-58509-063-1|pages=43–}}</ref> Some remains of the ruins of the canals can be seen in places around [[Lebanon]] and seems to be from the Roman times<ref name="AloufRain1999"/>
==Data==
Some of the canals were built in the second century during [[Hadrian]], when the region was fully under Roman rule. There are bridges over canals, still standing from Roman times<ref>[https://everipedia-storage.s3.amazonaws.com/NewlinkFiles/2636882/7edb1___canalizations-of-zenobia/roman-bridge-over-an-ancient-lebanese-canal-credit.jpe Roman bridge over canal supposed to be built under Zenobia]</ref>.
One of the canals is suggested to originate from a mountain near [[Labweh]] extending to [[Qusair]]<ref name="Abu-Izzeddin1963">{{cite book|author=Halim Said Abu-Izzeddin|title=Lebanon and its provinces: a study by the governors of the five provinces|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O1dtAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=1 October 2012|year=1963|publisher=Khayats}}</ref>. Labweh has several archaeological sites of interest including three old caves with [[Ancient Rome|Roman]]-[[Byzantine]] [[sarcophagi]] and the remains of a temple. There are also remains of a Byzantine bastion and a Roman dam suggested to date to the reign of [[Queen Zenobia]]. Legend suggests that channels were carved through the rock to send water to her lands in [[Palmyra]], Syria.<ref name="Brochure">[http://www.discoverlebanon.com/en/panoramic_views/bekaa/el_hermel/hermel-pyramid.php Ba'albeck - Al-Hermal, Bekaa - Tourist Brochure]</ref>
Another canal extends from the village of Chawaghir, {{convert|8|km|mi}} north of [[Hermel]].<ref>[http://www.mada.org.lb/resources/Hermel_survey_en.pdf Guadagnoli, Giulia, Hermel - Survey of social and economic establishments in 5 municipalities, MADA, January 2009]</ref> The canals were cut out of solid [[limestone]] bedrock to a depth of {{convert|20|m|ft}} with wells approximately every {{convert|100|m|ft}}.<ref>[http://www.nna-leb.gov.lb/archive/24-11-2010/E46.html Sahili, Jamal., (Translated by Lynn Waked), Hermel, The wealth of ancient monuments, Lebanese National News Agency, 24 November 2010.]</ref>
{{Quote|'' Among the remains to be found around Hermel one may see the canalizations of Zenobia, queen of Palmyra. Two of them hewn in the rock supplied the city of Palmyra in the desert with water from the Orontes. They were dug at a depth of twenty meters and were connected with wells dug at every hundred meters, channeling the water off to Palmyra, the short-lived capital of Queen Zenobia''.Kirkbride Diana <ref>Kirkbride, Diana. "Early Byblos and the Bakaa", Volume 45 (Pages 43–60), Mélanges de l'Université Saint-Joseph (Beirut Lebanon), 1969</ref>}}
The [[tradition]]al suggestion that the canals were originally constructed during the brief reign of Zenobia has been treated as probable -but not sure- by Michael Alouf, who notes the existence of canals traces in the desert around [[Palmyra]]<ref>[https://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2012/07/120717-palmyra-roman-city-syria-science-farming-world-ancient/ Canals found around Palmyra]</ref>, that are from the second century.<ref name="AloufRain1999"/>
The canals were used until the Arab conquest, when were destroyed.
